angles and predrill angled holes.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  BUILDING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  DIVIDING a room by erecting a partition wall requires moderate carpentry
skills but is seldom difficult. Planning and preparation are the keys.;   
Essentially, a partition wall consists of strips of lumber fastened together
to form a rectangular framework. This is strengthened by vertical strips,
called studs, installed at regular intervals inside the perimeter.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A ROOM DIVIDED: HOW TO ERECT WALL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The framework's top piece, called the plate, is attached to the ceiling;
its bottom piece, the sill, is attached to the floor. Doorways and other
openings are often included. Wallboard or some other paneling covers the
framework on both sides.;    If space permits, constructing the framework
horizontally and then tilting it into place for fastening to the ceiling and
floor is usually the easier method, because attaching the studs to the sill
and plate is simplified.;    But in most cases, lack of space dictates that
the framework be constructed vertically, beginning by attaching the plate and
sill to the ceiling and floor respectively, and then installing the studs
between them.;    How to begin;  Begin by checking with a local building
inspector to find out whether a building permit or inspection is needed and
whether you must include firestops.;    These are horizontal strips fastened
between the studs to prevent a wall from acting as a flue during a fire.
Installing wiring or plumbing inside a wall almost always requires both a
permit and an inspection before any paneling is attached.;    Next, estimate
and obtain materials. For a partition wall without plumbing, use 2-by-4
lumber; for a wall with plumbing, use 2-by-6 lumber. Specify straight boards;
warped boards are tricky or impossible to use. (Lumber yards will often allow
you to select the boards.);    Find the joists;  The wall described here has
no openings or firestops, and is constructed vertically. (Such a wall might
serve as a partial room divider.) To build it, you will need pieces for the
plate, two sills (installing a second sill on top of the first makes attaching
baseboard molding easier) and studs for each end and at 16-inch intervals
between them.;    Actual construction starts with determining the locations of
the ceiling beams, called joists, above the spot chosen for the wall. These
may be visible in an unfinished attic, or their locations may be detected on a
ceiling that has not recently been repainted as light-colored strips
separating darker areas.;    Other methods for finding joists include using an
electronic stud-finding tool or drilling test holes near corners where the
ceiling meets the walls. These can be concealed later.;    A wall running
perpendicular to ceiling joists or aligned so the plate lies directly below a
joist is easiest to fasten.;    Try to avoid erecting a wall between joists;
fastening it requires opening the ceiling and installing strips of wood
between the joists to provide anchoring surfaces for the plate. This is
usually a major task and involves repairing the ceiling.;    Installing the
plate;    Mark on the ceiling the position of joists the plate will cross or
the one it will lie beneath. Next, if the plate will cross the joists, mark on
it where fasteners installed through the plate will enter the joists; or if
the plate will lie beneath a joist, mark positions for fasteners along the
plate's center at 16- to 24-inch intervals.;    Installing the plate with
screws is easier than nailing it. Use screws if the ceiling is made of
plaster, because nailing into it may damage it.;    At the places marked,
drill holes through the plate for three-inch-long multipurpose or drywall
screws. With a helper, position the plate against the ceiling.;    While
holding the plate in place, insert a screw in one of the holes and drive it
into the joist with an electric drill with a screwdriver bit. Check the
alignment of the plate, then install the remaining screws.;    Use a plumb
bob;    Use a plumb bob to align the sill on the floor directly below the
plate. Have a helper hold the bob's string against one edge of the plate while
the bob itself dangles freely about an eighth of an inch from the floor. When
the bob stops moving, mark the floor directly below the point.;    Perform
this step at three or more places along the plate. Then draw a straight line
connecting as many of the points as possible. Align one of the two sills with
the line and screw or nail it to the floor. Then fasten the other sill on top
of it.;    Before installing the studs, mark their locations on the sill and
plate. Starting at one end, place studs so their centers are at 16-inch
intervals. (The distance between the final pair may be less.) Install the
studs by cutting and fastening them one at a time to accommodate
irregularities caused by an uneven floor or ceiling.;    Toenailing technique;
 Experienced carpenters usually fasten studs by driving nails at an angle
through their ends into the plate and sill, a difficult technique called
toenailing.;    An easier method is to fasten metal construction angles to the
ends of each stud (use two angles a stud), fit it into place, then nail the
protruding flanges of the angles to the plate and sill.;    Afterward, drill
an angled hole at the top and bottom of each of the stud's narrow edges and
install a screw or nail as with toenailing.;    Professional practice calls
for attaching end studs to existing wall framing, either a stud or wooden
strips installed as described for anchoring a plate between joists.;   
Amateurs can forgo this unless a code requires it. Once the framework is done
and any wiring or plumbing is installed, paneling can be applied.  </TEXT>
