<CAPTION>  Drawings (4); DRAWING: Choose folding stairs for occasional use and light
loads. Sliding staris wthstand freqeust use and heavy loads but require attic
space and above and in front.; DRAWING: Before installing stairs, strengthen
opening with headers and attach trimmer to narrow the opening if it is too
wide.; DRAWING: Raise stairs through opening and lower onto temporary ledgers.
Unfold, insert wood scraps to level and square frame in opening.; DRAWING:To
trim the bottom; ends of the stairs, measure and cut the ends at an angle so
they rest flat on the floor.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  HOUSING; REPAIR  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  INSTALLING a disappearing staircase -- stairs that fold down from a ceiling
hatchway and are raised into it for storage -- is worth considering if a
larger or more convenient attic entrance is needed.;   The job is usually not
too difficult for a moderately skilled amateur carpenter and a strong
assistant, provided a suitable hatchway already exists or can be built as
described below.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EASY STEPS: DISAPPEARING STAIRCASE MAKES ATTIC
ACCESSIBLE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Do It Yourself  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Disappearing staircases come in two styles. Both require at least three
feet of space in front of them at floor level for access.;   The folding style
consists of three staircase sections that fold together like accordion pleats.
These are suitable for occasional use (averaging no more than once or twice a
week) and where little room exists in the attic above or in front of the
hatchway.;   They generally cost $50 to $100, depending on quality and length,
and are usually rated for loads of about 200 pounds.;   For more frequent use
and heavier loads (up to 2,000 pounds), choose the sliding style. These have
only one section, which accounts for their increased strength.;   They also
have wider treads and a gentler slope than folding stairs, making them easier
to climb.;   Depending on their length, sliding stairs require three to six
feet of space above the hatchway and four to eight feet in front of it for
storage. They cost about $200 to $800.;   Both styles are spring-loaded to
make them easy to operate. The stairs can be obtained by ordering them through
a lumberyard or building supply store.;   To install disappearing stairs,
first draw an outline on the ceiling of the opening that must be cut for them.
Instructions furnished with the stairs will give the dimensions.;   If
possible, simply enlarge an existing opening. Consult a building inspector
before cutting a new one.;   Amateurs should create only rectangular openings
whose long sides run parallel to the ceiling joists. (Raise attic floorboards
to view the joists if necessary.);   For such openings, this usually involves
cutting through only one or two joists to create the opening's width; cutting
more requires bracing the ceiling from below to avoid collapse and is a job
for an expert carpenter.;   Position the opening so a joist will form one of
the long sides. Do this by drilling small holes as markers down from the attic
through the ceiling along the edge of the joist you select. At the same time,
reroute any electrical wiring that is in the way. When the outline is drawn,
cut along it with a saw. Sever joists squarely.;   Have on hand three pieces
of lumber the same dimensions as the joists -- usually 2-by-8 or 2-by-10 stock
-- and also a supply of U-shaped metal joist hangers and nails designed for
them. Home centers and lumberyards carry these items.;   Cut two pieces of the
lumber for headers to strengthen the opening and support the severed joists.
Cut the headers to span the width of the opening; then loosely fasten a joist
hanger at both ends of each header by installing the nails only partway. Also
attach joist hangers loosely to the ends of the severed joists.;   Set the
headers in place so their edges are even with those of the joists. Nail
through the hangers' flanges into the joists perpendicular to them, then
finish hammering any partly driven nails. Fasten the severed joists to the
headers the same way.;   Use the third piece as a trimmer to narrow the
opening if it is too wide. Cut it to fit between the headers; fasten it to
them with joist hangers.;   With folding stairs, the next step is to
temporarily attach ledgers -- two strips of 1-by-4 lumber -- to the ceiling at
each end projecting into the opening at a 90-degree angle to header.;  
Position each ledger so it creates a lip about three-quarters of an inch wide
beneath the opening, and attach it with nails or screws to the header above.; 
 With help from an assistant, maneuver the folded staircase sideways through
the opening from below, then twist and lower it into place onto the ledgers.
(Most staircases weigh about 60 pounds.);   Gently unfold the staircase as
much as possible (it should be too long) and anchor it temporarily by driving
a few eight-penny (2 1/2 inches long) finishing nails through the frame into
the ceiling opening. Leave the nails protruding for easy removal.;   Level and
square the staircase frame inside the opening by inserting wood scraps between
the frame and the opening where necessary.;   Permanently fasten the frame to
the joists and headers with 16-penny (3 1/2-inch) common nails spaced about 10
inches apart. Then remove the finishing nails or drive them fully into the
wood.;   To trim the stairway to the correct length, first lock the top and
middle sections into position. Set a yardstick on the top edge of one of the
stair's sides and extend it to the floor.;   Next, measure the distance
spanned by the yardstick between the end of the stair and the floor, and mark
the same distance on the upper edges of both sides of the lower section by
measuring from its hinged end. Repeat the process on the underside of the
stairs to mark the lower edges.;   On each side of the section, draw slanting
lines connecting the upper and lower marks. Then carefully saw along them to
remove excess material from the bottom.;   Refold the stairs slightly so the
lower section can be fully unfolded; the trimmed ends should rest flat on the
floor.;   Sliding stairs have no frame and are not preassembled. Basically,
installation involves first attaching the hatchway door and stair hinge to the
forward part of the ceiling opening.;   Next, the stairs are assembled on the
floor, raised into place and fastened to the hinge. Finally, the spring cables
are attached and adjusted. Complete instructions are supplied by the
manufacturer.;   After installing either type of stairs, trim the perimeter of
the hatchway with molding.  </TEXT>
