<DESCRIPT>  HOUSING; GARDEN; CONSTRUCTION; QA  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Q I want to install a porch swing. The porch-roof ceiling has the old-style
tongue-and-groove wood strips. Will the boards hold a swing and what kind of
hardware should I use?;    A The tongue-and-groove boards won't support a
swing adequately, but the ceiling joists, to which the boards are nailed,
should. Nailing patterns will sometimes reveal the locations of joists, but
nail heads might not be visible in the tongue-and-groove boards.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PORCH SWING NEEDS STRONG SUPPORT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Do It Yourself
Gene Austin writes about real estate and home improvement for the Philadelphia
Inquirer.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     If not, thump the ceiling with your knuckles or a screwdriver handle until
you hit a solid spot, or use a magnetic or electronic stud finder, sold at
many home centers and hardware stores. Once you find one joist, others should
be spaced at 16-inch intervals from it. To confirm the presence of solid wood,
drill a test hole  or 1/16in diameter. The joists are probably 2-by-6s or
2-by-4s.;    Swings are generally suspended from heavy-duty eye bolts or
screw-eyes (a bolt needs a nut on the end, a screw doesn't).;    I suggest
screw-eyes with screws at least four inches long and shanks and eyes of
three-eighths-inch steel. One screw-eye is needed for each end of the swing.
The distance between screw-eyes should be approximately the length of the
swing, but joist spacing might make it necessary to make this distance a
little more or less. Drill  -inch pilot holes for the screw-eyes, making
certain you hit solid wood.;    The swing chains are suspended from the eyes
with heavy-duty S hooks at least a quarter-inch in diameter. The S hooks make
it easy to hang or remove the swing, or adjust its height.;    Test the
installation carefully and check it frequently to make sure everything is
secure.  </TEXT>
