<CAPTION>  Diagram; DIAGRAM: A cut nail, inset, works best when driven into mortar joints
between bricks or concrete blocks.; Pre-drill holes for concrete screws.
Length of screws should be twice the thickness of the lumber.; Anchor bolt
with expanding lead shield requires two holes, top. Others require a single
hole.; The toggle bolt for use with hollow concrete blocks grips from behind.
These resemble a T.; A powder-actuated fastening tool will drive the nail by
detonating a .22-caliber cartridge.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CONSTRUCTION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ATTACHING wood to concrete or other masonry can be the most challenging part
of remodeling a basement or applying paneling over brick. Choosing the right
fastener can make all the difference. Several types are made.;   For many
jobs, such as mounting furring strips (1-by-3-inch boards for supporting
paneling) or 2-by-4s, masonry nails, cut nails or concrete screws are adequate.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NAILING DOWN THE BEST METHOD FOR ATTACHING WOOD TO
CONCRETE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Do It Yourself  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Masonry nails resemble ordinary nails with flat heads, but are thicker,
grooved and made of hardened steel. For driving into solid concrete, choose
nails long enough to penetrate three-quarters to one inch. For driving into
brick and concrete-block masonry, choose nails long enough to penetrate about
an inch and a quarter. (In brick and block, drive nails only into mortar
joints, not into the bricks or blocks; these may shatter.);   When installing
masonry nails in narrow lumber or near the ends of boards, first drill nail
holes through the wood; this will keep the wood from splitting. Make the holes
slightly smaller in diameter than the thickness of the nails.;   Cut nails are
rectangular in cross section and have flat tapering sides and blunt points.
They hold well in mortar joints but are difficult to drive into solid
concrete. When driven through lumber with their tapering sides parallel to the
wood grain, cut nails are less likely than masonry nails to cause splitting,
and so do not always require pre-drilled holes.;   To attach a board using
masonry or cut nails, space the fasteners 18 to 24 inches apart. Drill holes
through the wood if desired, then install one or two nails in the board before
setting it in place. At least one of the nails should be near the center of
the board to support it while you nail the others. To drive masonry and cut
nails, use a small sledgehammer. Wear goggles.;   Hammer the first nails into
the masonry, then continue with the rest. Drive nails only until their heads
are flush with the board's surface; hammering farther can loosen them.;  
Concrete screws are sometimes easier to use than nails, and can be installed
in brick and block. The first step is to drill holes for the screws. If you
need only a few holes an ordinary variable-speed drill is adequate, but for
larger jobs rent an electric hammer drill. Choose screws that are twice as
long as the lumber is thick.;   To install a concrete screw, hold the board in
place and drill through it into the masonry using a masonry-drilling bit with
a carbide tip. The diameter of the bit must equal that of the screw's shaft
minus the threads. Then install the screw and tighten it firmly. If
overtightened, the screw may pull loose.;   Boards thicker than 1 1/2 inches
or boards that must support greater weight than paneling or wallboard require
expansion fasteners. Among the strongest are anchor bolts with lead shields;
these consist of a sturdy bolt and a cylindrical lead sleeve (the shield),
which is split in half along part of its length.;   Anchor bolts are available
at hardware stores and can be installed in concrete, mortar and bricks, but
not concrete block. To select the right size and quantity, ask a sales clerk
for the manufacturer's recommendations. As with concrete screws, you will need
an electric drill and a masonry-drilling bit.;   To install anchor bolts,
pre-drill the board. Use the holes as a guide for marking the masonry with a
center punch or nail. Then bore larger holes into the masonry for the
shields.;   Tap the shields into place with a hammer until they are flush with
or just below the masonry surface. Place a washer on each bolt and slide the
bolts through the board into the shields. Tighten all the bolts as a group, a
little at a time, until all are snug. Tightening the fastener causes the
halves of the shield to expand against the sides of the hole, securing the
assembly.;   Other anchor bolts require drilling only one hole. A special bolt
and shield are installed as a unit; then, depending on the design, tightening
to spread the shield's halves is done with a wrench, screwdriver or hammer.;  
On walls made of hollow concrete block, use toggle bolts that grip from
behind. These resemble a T. The short segment (the toggle) pivots so it can be
aligned end-to-end with the long segment (the bolt), which is threaded.;   To
install, drill a hole the same diameter as the bolt through the board and into
the block. Attach a washer and nut to the bolt, then push the bolt toggle-end
first into the hole. When the toggle enters the cavity inside the block it
will fall, pivoting until it is perpendicular to the bolt. Tightening the nut
then will draw the toggle against the block's inside surface while compressing
the board against the outside.;   Another method of fastening lumber up to 1
1/2 inches thick to masonry is to use a powder-actuated fastening tool that
fires special nails with a .22-caliber gunpowder cartridge.;   A
powder-actuated fastening tool, sold at hardware stores for $15 and up, is a
good investment for some jobs that would otherwise require installing many
masonry nails or screws. Besides lessening the effort of such a job, using the
tool eliminates vibration from hammering that can loosen previously driven
nails.;   Before using a powder-actuated tool, carefully read the instructions
and safety precautions. Also practice nailing. To operate one popular model,
press the end containing the nail against the surface to be fastened and
strike the other end with an ordinary hammer. This detonates the cartridge.  </TEXT>
