<P>
HANDYMEN SHOULD STICK CLOSE TO THEIR GLUE GUNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By A.J. HAND, A.J. Hand writes for the Los Angeles Times Syndicate. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Next time you tackle a construction job around the home, reach for your gun. 
I'm talking about your caulking gun. Load it up with one of a variety of 
specialized construction adhesives now available in caulking gun cartridges, 
and you'll have a potent tool for shooting down a wide variety of construction 
problems. Examples? 
</P>
<P>
Decking: The traditional way to fasten down deck planking is with two nails at 
every joist. This holds the planks down, at least initially, but with time, it 
also causes problems. One is splitting. Another is rust. Even the best 
hot-dipped galvanized nails will rust eventually. This causes stains and 
eventual deterioration of the decking. Nails can also work loose, pop up and 
injure bare feet. 
</P>
<P>
The answer to all these problems is deck adhesive, a special formula designed 
to work well with pressure-treated stock. Using this adhesive won't eliminate 
the need for nails entirely. You'll still need a few here and there (follow 
directions on the glue cartridge) to restrain warped boards and keep good 
contact between planking and joists. But you'll use far fewer nails than you 
would without adhesive, and you'll get a stronger, more durable job in the 
bargain. 
</P>
<P>
Sub-flooring: Here's another ideal application for construction adhesive. 
Typical floor construction calls for one layer of five-eighths or sometimes 
half-inch plywood followed by another layer of plywood under-layment to provide 
a smooth base for your finish flooring. By using adhesive and special 
three-quarter-inch tongue-and-groove plywood, you can do the job with just one 
layer. The adhesive should go on all joists, plus along the mating edges of the 
plywood sheets. Nail according to adhesive instructions and you'll get a 
sturdy, squeak-free floor with less labor than required for the old-fashioned 
two-layer system. 
</P>
<P>
Finishing off walls: There are also special adhesives for installing drywall 
and paneling. I always like to use at least a few fasteners when installing 
drywall, but with paneling, you may be able to get by without any nails at all, 
using this trick: 
</P>
<P>
Run a fat bead of adhesive on each stud and the panel in place, pressing it 
firmly into the adhesive. Immediately pull the panel away to let the adhesive 
dry for a short time (this varies according to brand). Then press the panel 
back in place. When you do, it will stick like, well . . . glue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
