<LEADPARA>  Q How can I get the mildew smell out of a mattress that was stored in the
cellar? I don't see mildew, but I sure can smell it.;    A Bleach and sunshine
should take care of it. And, as you have learned, a mattress should not be
stored in a basement. Make a solution of one part bleach and 3 to six parts
water. Dip a sponge in it, squeeze it out and wipe all surfaces of the
mattress. Leave the mattress in direct sun for as long as practical. If the
mildew is on the inside of the mattress, it is unlikely that you will ever get
the odor out. Wear rubber gloves when working with bleach.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MILDEW MEETS ITS MATCH IN BLEACH AND SUNSHINE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Interiors  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Q I found a few medium-sized carpenter ants in a porch post, and several
big ones in the house. The bottom of the post was soft, and I think I found
the nest and applied granular Diazinon and wiped it out. How can I keep the
ants away? And how can I fix the post?;    A You can't be sure the ants are
carpenters without identification, but it's safe to say yours are carpenters.
The ones in the house might be lost; the ones in the post were right where
carpenters ants like to work: damp, punky wood. If there is no other punky
wood on or in the house, chances are fair that you won't get carpenter ants.; 
  For the post, shore up the roof of the porch with temporary 2-by-4 or 4-by-4
braces, and check to see how far the decay of the post has gone. If it is just
a few inches, cut it off until you get to sound, dry wood, and install a thick
base in place of the old base, or put in a large base and a slightly smaller
base on top of that. If the decay has gone up more than a few inches, replace
the entire post.;    Q I chipped out a section of plaster ceiling three feet
long and 15 inches wide where a leak from the bathroom above softened it in my
1950s house. The plaster is only about 1/8-inch thick, and underneath is a
grainy, coarse plaster that is darker. Can I replaster that section?;    A You
certainly can cover that area, if the coarse plaster is not crumbling or
powdering. The coarse plaster is a scratch or brown coat of a real plaster
ceiling. Use joint compound to fill the space. Buy a rectangular plasterer's
trowel to do a decent job of applying the joint compound. Dampen the coarse
plaster and apply the joint compound with the big trowel. Wait a few minutes
and smooth it off so that it is level with the original surface. After
everything is dry, sand ridges and bumps. Wait at least two weeks before
painting the ceiling with two thin coats of latex ceiling paint.;    Q Can
siding be put over old asbestos cement shingles?;    A Some outfits put vinyl
siding over asbestos cement shingles, but I think it's a bad thing to do.
Nailing into asbestos shingles will break them up, and asbestos fibers could
be released, something that should be avoided. If the shingles break up,
pieces may drop out of position and get stuck, preventing a smooth surface for
the new siding. Predrilling holes through the asbestos for the nails of the
new siding is just as bad or worse, releasing fibers into the air. An
alternative is to have the shingles removed (very expensive) and new shingles
or clapboards put up over the original finish. Another alternative is to paint
the asbestos cement shingles with two coats of latex house paint.;    Q I plan
to put a railing on the deck on my Victorian house (it's the original "This
Old House"), and I'd like to make it Victorian like the house itself. Where
can I get fancy spindles and rails? How far apart should they be?;    A You
can get fancy turned spindles or balusters at almost any lumber store; some
have special displays set up and you can take your choice. Most are
pressure-treated wood, which is OK to use in this application. There are many
styles of balusters and rails to match, both top rail and bottom rail, the
latter raised a few inches above the floor. The rails are rounded on the top
for water runoff. And, there are posts that hold the rails in place. Balusters
can be close together or far apart, but close enough to keep little heads from
getting stuck between them. Put them 4 inches on center, meaning the center of
one is 4 inches from the center of its neighbor. If the balusters are 1 1/2
inches wide, there will be 2 1/2 inches of space between them. Of course, you
will want to space the balusters so the space will be the same from one end of
the rail to the other.  </TEXT>
