<HEAD>Man Shot In Head With Nail Gun Should Be OK, Doctor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nail accidentally fired from a nail gun
penetrated about 1{ inches into a carpenter's brain and nailed his
cap to his head, but the doctor who removed the nail said he
shouldn't suffer any serious effects.
   ``I've had worse headaches,'' said carpenter Lance Grangruth,
who said the headache was the only complication he suffered.
   ``I didn't actually feel it go in,'' he said. ``I heard the gun
go off.
   ``I tried to take my hat off and it wouldn't come off. Then I
knew it had gone in.''
   Dr. William Himango said he used pliers Monday to remove the
2-inch nail from the frontal lobe of Grangruth's brain at St.
Luke's Hospital. Grangruth, of Barnum, was kept in intensive care
for observation.
   ``If he were to pick a place to put a nail in, he picked exactly
the right place to put it in,'' Himango said.
   The same injury to other parts of the brain could have caused
functional damage or death, Himango said.
   Grangruth was working on a garage Monday in Hermantown when a
co-worker, perched on a ladder, lowered his arm while holding the
gun's trigger, said police Officer Dan Perich. The co-worker didn't
realize Grangruth was standing below.
   Although the co-worker was holding the regular trigger, a nail
gun won't fire until a safety trigger at the muzzle also is
depressed by pushing it against the work surface where the nail is
wanted.
   When the gun touched Grangruth's head it went off, with 120
pounds of air pressure driving an 8-penny galvanized nail _ about
an eighth-inch thick _ through his baseball cap and into his
forehead.
   Grangruth and his co-worker went to a nearby house to call an
ambulance.
   Perich found Grangruth alert and a little pale, but not bleeding.
   ``He was sitting on the couch talking,'' Perich said. ``He
walked around with the nail in his head.''
</TEXT>
