<DESCRIPT>  HOUSING; REPAIR  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  REPLACING an outside door -- for appearance, security or energy efficiency --
may sound like a daunting task. But home centers and building-supply stores
carry pre-hung entry doors, already mounted in a frame, that amateurs with
some carpentry experience will find quite easy to install.;    Before ordering
the door, you need to measure the doorway in several places. Door frames are
seldom exactly true -- perfectly vertical and horizontal -- so determine the
average height and width.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  REPLACING A DOOR IS NOT A DAUNTING TASK  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     For the average height, measure in two places from the underside of the
frame at the top of the doorway to the base of the threshold's saddle directly
below, or to the floor if the threshold is removable.;    For the average
width, measure in three places between the inside surfaces of the door frame's
sides, or jambs. These will be the surfaces that the door's edges touch when
it is closed.;    When you receive the door, open the carton carefully to
inspect it and study the manufacturer's instructions. Do not remove any clips
or other retainers fastening the door to the frame.;    Begin the installation
by removing the existing door and all hardware attached to the frame. Also pry
off the interior casing -- the molding surrounding the doorway inside the
building. If the casing is intact, it can be reused.;    The instructions
supplied with the door will specify how to modify the existing threshold to
accept the pre-hung door frame.;    Using shims;    If you are working with
the old door frame, you will usually need to nail thin wooden wedges called
shims to the jambs so the pre-hung door frame will fit closely in the
doorway.;    Shims are available at lumberyards, but they come with most doors
of this kind, along with a chart telling how many to use.;    Apply caulking
compound to the surface beneath the new door's threshold. Now the pre-hung
door and frame can be inserted into the doorway.;    Before it is fastened,
the frame of the pre-hung door must be trued with a builder's level. First,
place the level on top of the door frame to see that it is horizontal, then
alongside the door to see that it is vertical. If it is not, install more
shims behind the top and sides of the frame to brace it in the correct
position.;    When the adjustments are made, drive tenpenny (2-inch) common
nails, or those supplied, through the pre-drilled holes in the new frame to
attach it to the existing frame.;    Then open the door and install long
screws (also usually supplied) through the the predrilled holes in the sides
and top of the door frame to fasten it completely. When the door is closed,
the heads of the fasteners will be hidden.;    If the existing door frame has
to come off, you will need a helper, who need not be skilled, to install the
pre-hung door. Pry away the door frame and exterior trim to expose the studs
around the opening.;    Apply caulk;    Modify the existing threshold as
specified in the instructions; then apply caulk to the surface that beneath
the threshold of the pre-hung door.;    With the helper standing inside the
house, set the pre-hung door and frame into the doorway from the outside. Hold
a builder's level alongside the vertical brick mold (the molding that overlaps
the studs forming the doorway) on the door's hinge side.;    Have the helper
adjust the door frame until the level shows that both the face and an adjacent
edge of the brick mold are vertical.;    Then fasten the brick mold to the
stud on the hinge side of the opening by driving a 16-penny (3 1/2-inch)
galvanized finishing nail through the brick mold, perpendicular to the siding,
at the top, middle and bottom of the frame.;    From inside, fill any gap
between the door frame and the opening by inserting shims at each hinge
location and also at the top and bottom of the jamb.;    Then go outside and
at each of the shim locations drive a pair of 16-penny galvanized finishing
nails through the jamb and shims and into the stud, parallel to the siding.;  
 Open the door and adjust the remaining jamb from outside so the molding or
weatherstripping touching the door makes even contact with it all the way
around.;    Proper gaps;    There should be a gap of three-eighths of an inch
between the bottom of the door and the threshold, and a gap of three
thirty-seconds of an inch between the latch side of the door and the frame.;  
 Then nail through the brick mold or flanges, add shims from inside and fasten
the jamb permanently. Pack any gaps between shims with fiberglass insulation.;
   Now mount the door hardware, reattach the interior casing and any other
trim, and add weatherstripping or caulking as specified in the instructions.
And your new door is ready, usually after no more than an afternoon's work.  </TEXT>
