<DESCRIPT>  GARDEN; REPAIR; EQUIPMENT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  USING screws instead of nails for fastening decks and other outdoor
woodworking projects will often give a neater appearance and reduce some
maintenance problems.;    Screwed-together decks have several advantages over
nailed construction, including extra strength and simpler disassembly if
repairs are needed. Top-quality screws also reduce or eliminate rust and
corrosion of fasteners, which are common even with hot-dipped galvanized nails
because hammer blows can chip the coating.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TOP-QUALITY FASTENERS REDUCE RUST, CORROSION
SCREWS BEAT NAILS FOR DECKS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Do It Yourself  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Some home centers and building-supply outlets sell decking screws with
Phillips-style heads (X-shaped slots), treated for weather resistance by
galvanizing or other plating processes. Stainless-steel screws are also
available but are relatively expensive.;    All deck screws have slim,
straight shanks and coarse threads for easy driving, and the thin heads sink
fairly easily into decking without countersinking. Pilot holes, slightly
smaller than the screw diameter, make driving easier and prevent splitting,
especially when screws are used close to edges and ends of boards.;    Deck
builders who want to go a step further can use what might well be the best
deck screw so far.;    Good grip, control;    The head of this rust-resistant
screw features a combination square drive and Phillips drive -- a deep, square
recess in the head that gives excellent grip and control with a square-end
driver. The screw head also has notches at the corners of the recess so that a
Phillips driver can be used if a square driver is not available.;    The head
design, called Square-X by one manufacturer, virtually eliminates slipping if
a square driver is used, which means a power screwdriver will not jump out of
the head and mar decking boards.;    A source of Square-X screws in lengths
from 1 1/4-inch to three inches, as well as square-tip drivers and bits, is
Woodworkers' Store, Industrial Boulevard, Rogers, Minn. 55374. A catalog is
$1, refundable with a product order.;    Power driving is almost essential
when using screws for decks or other projects in which many screws must be
driven.;    I have had good results using a variable-speed, cordless
drill-driver that has the proper speed and torque for driving screws. A
regular variable-speed drill can also be used, but the high torque can drive
screws too deeply into the wood and, unless a square driver is used, can also
cause the bit to skip out of screw heads.;    Stop that screw;    One
solution, if a regular power drill must be used, is to equip it with a clutch
adapter that causes the driver to stop turning when the screw is properly
seated. A clutch adapter costs $20 to $25. A source is Leichtung Workshops,
4944 Commerce Parkway, Cleveland, Ohio 44128 (catalog free).;    When 2-by-4s
are used for decking, some builders save time and fasteners with a zigzag
fastening system. In this system, only one screw or nail is driven through the
deck board into each intersection with the beam or joist underneath (beams are
usually centered 16 inches apart).;    Each fastener is spaced about
three-quarters of an inch from the edge of the deck board, first near one
edge, then near the opposite edge at the next joint, forming a neat zigzag
pattern. However, if boards wider than 2-by-4s are used, I prefer two
fasteners at each beam joint to help prevent warping and twisting.;    New
treatment for wood;    One of the newer products for deck builders is
pressure-treated wood that is treated for water repellency as well as
resistance to wood-damaging insects and rot. Hickson Corp.'s Wolmanized Extra
is an example. The factory-applied water-repellency treatment is intended to
help combat the splitting and twisting that mar the appearance of many
projects built with pressure-treated wood.;    A problem is that users of this
extra-cost, pressure-treated wood might assume that the water-repellency
treatment is as long-range as the treatment for rot and insects. Actually,
follow-up treatments with a water-repellent sealer will be needed to give the
wood full protection.;    Manufacturers have been somewhat fuzzy on when
follow-up treatments are needed for the special wood. Hickson Corp. recently
made these comments, which help clarify the matter: "Even these new products
cannot prevent weather damage forever. . . . Foot traffic and sunshine breaks
down the water repellency at the wood's surface.;    "Periodic application
(every year or two, depending on conditions) of a topical water repellent
restores surface protection and keeps a wood deck looking its best."  </TEXT>
