<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Rapper Ice-T performed songs from his new record, 'O.G.
Original Gangster,' as part of the Lollapalooza tour at Shoreline.; PHOTO:
Jane's Addiction ended the show with a magnetic -- yet bothersome --
performance.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  'LOLLAPALOOZA" is one of those words that defies specific definition but whose
meaning is obvious anyway. Think of the word for a moment; now think of the
tour of the same name. It fits.;    The Lollapalooza tour came to Shoreline
Amphitheater for shows Friday and Saturday. And, yes, it was a "lollapalooza"
in just about every way.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHAT A LOLLAPALOOZA!  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Music Review  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     It was big: Seven groups performed onstage, with scores of extra groups
doing their various things on the concourse, along with activist organizations
like Rock The Vote and Greenpeace. It was brash: Schiavo Hair Dressing At
Large (a holdover hit from the recent event Gathering of the Tribes) sculpted
and moussed the fans' hair on a stage on the concourse; and the avant-gardists
of Piano Bell From Hell slammed away at various destroyed keyboards and yelled
obscenities.;    And Lollapalooza was a hit: Friday's show was a sellout to
the tune of 20,000 fans, and Saturday's was nearly the same.;    But what
really set this tour apart from its counterparts, such as Tribes and Operation
Rock &amp; Roll, was that Lollapalooza made a musical point. And that point, too,
was a lollapalooza.;    The point was that rock 'n' roll hasn't necessarily
come to a dead end. All of the groups of this tour were at the cutting edge of
pop. In their ways, each was proof that there are, perhaps, new ideas to be
explored and that they are being explored.;    And, in their ways, each group
was making rock that was infused with energy and excitement and provocation.
It didn't make all of them good, necessarily, but it made each of them
intriguing.;    The Rollins Band opened the day with a slashing sound that
served as the backdrop and counterpoint to leader Rollins' vocal histrionics.
The former Black Flag member shouted the words to the songs with an intensity
and fervor that were compelling. It was an abrasive set, with metallic chords
and monolithic rhythms, almost rock as some sort of expressive release. It
wasn't pretty, but then, it wasn't intended to be.;    The Texas-based
Butthole Surfers came next, with a musical assault that was equally abrasive,
but more orchestrated. Vocalist Gibby Haynes spent most of his time intoning
his words into a bullhorn, while the rest of the group created a cacophonous
sound that was raw and unlistenable. It wasn't rock as much as noise.;   
Ice-T rap;  "We didn't come here to party for you; we came to party with you,"
rapper Ice-T yelled at the start of his set. He said much else, most of which
is unprintable in a family newspaper. Performing songs from his new record
"O.G. Original Gangster," Ice-T baited the crowd with raps laced liberally
with the "F" and "N" words. But when he closed his performance with his new
heavy metal group, Body Count, he churned out blaring, edgy rock that proved a
point of its own. "Rock has nothing to do with color," he shouted. "It is a
state of mind.";    The real hit of this show -- in every way -- was Nine Inch
Nails. Performing on a hi-tech set that came with strobes and fog (that was
blown out at the crowd), the group created an industrial sound that clanked
and bonked electronically but that also had a melodic grandeur and thematic
cohesion that engaged the mind as much as the solar plexus. Leader Trent
Reznor was a maniac speaking his vocals like an automaton while hurling
guitars and drinking cups and mic stands at his mates. The violence was
innocent and disturbing; when paired with the dense and mechanistic songs, it
resulted in a set that was electrifying.;    Pop-tinged metal;  Of all the
groups, Living Colour and Siouxsie and the Banshees were the most
anachronistic, but just barely. Living Colour's metal was pop-tinged and
driven by the instrumental virtuosity of guitarist Vernon Reid. But Reid's
furious forays of sound, notwithstanding, the group seemed somewhat arch and
staid compared with the confrontational music of Rollins and the rest.;    The
punk siren, Siouxisie, seemed similarly innocuous. Even the exotic songs of
the new album "Superstition" had an older feel with their complex
juxtapositions of punk and Eastern themes. But while Siouxsie was dated,
somewhat, that was tolerable because, as one of the original punks of '70s
London, she is one of the progenitors of the rest of Lollapalooza's legions.; 
  Alluring Jane's Addiction;  The spearhead of the tour was Jane's Addiction
and they closed the event with a performance that was annoying -- and
entrancing. The songs of "Ritual de lo Habitual" were a varied lot, ranging
from nervy, noisy rockers to brooding ballads, all of which had a
thrash/punk/metal bite and bluster. And with two female dancers cavorting amid
looming, swaying palm trees and statues, there was a visual allure that made
the group and its songs seem mysterious. But the sophomoric mumblings of Perry
Farrell about sex and, ah, size and such were constantly distracting. And his
helium vocals were an inadvertent hoot -- he sounded like a cross between
Johnny Rotten and a punkish Pee Wee Herman.;    But good or bad, all of the
groups of Lollapalooza were doing their best to inspire and provoke. Their
music was a slap in the face. Thanks, rock needs that.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  HARRY SUMRALL, Mercury News Music Writer  </BYLINE>
