<LEADPARA>  CONVENTIONAL clothes closets, with one high shelf and a single rod for
hangers, waste space and become cluttered too easily. Both problems can be
solved by dividing the closet into compartments with freestanding storage
units or a combination of built-in units and rods.;    First reorganize the
closet's contents. Sort all items into two groups: those that are used in the
same room as the closet, and those that are not. Move the items used elsewhere
closer to their area of use if possible.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FIND HIDDEN STORAGE AREAS
CREATIVE IDEAS FOR CRAMPED CLOSETS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Interiors  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     If no one has used the remaining items in the last year, can they be
discarded? If you don't want to get rid of them, perhaps you can store them
elsewhere.;    When the only items left are those that must remain, rehang the
clothes with the longest at one end of the rod and the shortest at the other.;
   Items that are seldom used or are out of season can be grouped in hanging
storage bags. Then stand several feet away and look over the area above and
beneath the clothes. This is the closet's extra storage space.;   
Freestanding storage;  The simplest way to use this space is to fill it with
freestanding storage units like shelves, baskets, racks and trays. Modular
units can be bought at home centers, department stores and stores specializing
in closet accessories.;    But if you are handy, you can usually save money by
making storage units. Following are directions for simple shelving units
resembling small bookcases.;    Out of three-quarter-inch-thick plywood, saw
two rectangles for the sides of the unit and another for the top. The length
of the sides should equal the intended height of the unit minus three-quarters
of an inch, and the width should equal the unit's intended depth.;    Shelving
that is installed below shoulder height can be as deep as the closet itself
(usually 22 to 24 inches), but overhead shelves should not be more than 20
inches deep; otherwise, reaching into them may be difficult.;    Make the top
the same width as the sides. The length should be the desired width of the
unit (but no more than 34 inches, to keep the shelves from sagging).;   
Decide how many shelves you want, and how far apart they should be. Convenient
distances between shelves are 6, 9 and 12 inches. Saw the shelves from
three-quarter-inch plywood, and make them an inch and a half shorter than the
length of the top.;    Support strips;    For each shelf saw a pair of
one-inch-wide support strips, or cleats. These should be as long as the sides
are wide. If you think you might want to hang the unit from a wall rather than
make it freestanding, cut another cleat (called a hanging bar) two inches wide
and the length of a shelf.;    Last, cut a rectangle of quarter-inch-thick
hardboard (one brand is Masonite) for the back of the unit. Its dimensions
should equal the unit's full intended height and width.;    To assemble the
unit, first position the wide surfaces of the cleats against the sides,
three-fourths of an inch below the intended heights of the shelves, and attach
them with dry-wall or multipurpose screws one and a quarter inches long. These
are most easily driven with an electric drill with a screwdriver bit.;   
Next, fasten the top across the upper ends of the sides, using
two-and-a-quarter-inch screws. Position the hanging bar against the underside
of the top, flush with the rear edges of the top and sides.;    Fasten the bar
by driving two-and-a-quarter-inch screws into its ends through the unit's
sides.;    Final steps;    Finally, position the back with its edges flush
with those of the sides and top and attach it with three-quarter-inch wire
nails. Paint the unit if desired, and then insert the shelves. Stand it in the
closet, or if you wish, attach it to the wall with the hanging bar as
described farther on.;    For maximum storage space and convenience, consider
partitioning the closet vertically and replacing the single rod and upper
shelf with several short rods and storage units.;    Multiple rods can be used
to hang short items of clothing in double rows, and placing storage units
nearer the top of the closet, rather than at the bottom, eliminates stooping.;
   To plan a layout, make a scale drawing on graph paper. Draw a rectangle
representing the closet's sides, top and floor. Next, group the clothing by
length and hang it from the rod. Measure the width of each group.;    Then
measure the distance from the bottom of the longest item in each group to the
floor; to that distance, add the distance from the top of the closet down to
any shelving above the clothes rod.;    Measuring to scale on the drawing,
come down this total distance from the line representing the top of the
closet. Draw horizontal lines across the rectangle, as long as the width of
each group of clothes; these lines will be stepped, indicating the bottom of
the clothing.;    Another look;  Turn the sketch upside down. Now the space
beneath the clothing appears at the top, and the stepped lines represent the
heights at which short rods should be hung.;    Remove the rod and upper shelf
and install purchased or homemade storage nits whose sides divide the closet
vertically at the intervals suggested by the widths of the clothing groups. To
fasten units to a wall, install two two-and-a-half-inch screws through each
hanging bar into studs inside the wall.;    If the positions of the studs do
not allow this, or if purchased units have metal corner brackets instead of a
hanging bar, as in the illustration at above right, make cleats long enough to
span the studs and attach these horizontally to the wall first (nailing or
screwing them to studs).;    Then attach the units to the cleats. Two cleats
are needed for each unit: an upper one for fastening and a lower one to hold
the bottom of the unit out from the wall, so it hangs vertically.;    Attach
short rods between the partitions at heights that allow the longest item in
each clothing group to hang clear of the floor.  </TEXT>
