<LEADPARA>  RINGO Starr is back in the studio again, recording a new solo album. The
record, untitled at the moment, is his first solo record since 1981's "Stop
And Smell the Roses." (A live record of his 1989 tour, "Ringo Starr and His
All-Starr Band," was released in 1990.) The new record is part of a long-term
deal that the former drummer for the Beatles has concluded with the Private
Music label.;    Producing the new record is Jeff Lynne, who was responsible
for "Cloud Nine," George Harrison's remarkable 1987 comeback record. Ringo has
had an uneven solo career, with hits such as "Photograph" and "It Don't Come
Easy," but misses as well. But with Lynne -- who has a way of re-creating the
old Beatle charm -- on line, Ringo could be in for a comeback.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RINGO COMES BACK WITH NEW PRODUCER  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Pop Music  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     THEY OUGHTA BE IN PICTURES -- Think of the two big pop stars that you would
most like to see in the movies. They would have to be Whitney Houston and
Vanilla Ice, wouldn't they? Hold that laughter down a minute, because that's
just what they're going to do. Houston is set to make her screen debut in "The
Bodyguard," with the co-star being none other than Oscar-winner Kevin Costner.
The movie, which begins shooting in November, is a thriller about an ex-Secret
Service agent who is hired to protect a big-name pop vocalist from an
obsessive fan.;    And that hit-making ice-man Vanilla Ice, hot on the heels
of his first movie ("Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles II"), will star in "Cool As
Ice," which is described as "a mix of music, romance and dance." The movie
should have its premiere later this year.;    While we're at it, Ice's new
album, "Vanilla Ice Extremely Live," is set for a June 4 release. The album is
the follow-up to his debut, "To The Extreme," which sold 11 million copies.
The new album comes with live versions of the Ice's hits and four new studio
songs, including -- hold your breath -- Vanilla's rendition of the Rolling
Stones' "Satisfaction.";    OFF WITH THE SHOWS -- If you were one of the
10,000 fans at Shoreline Amphitheater on Monday disappointed when Whitney
Houston's show was canceled, the official word from Bill Graham Presents is
laryngitis.;    Also, Poison's show at Shoreline tonight has been canceled
because of illness, a BGP spokesman said Wednesday. Tickets will be refunded
at place of purchase.;    TOUR TIME -- Two of the Bay Area's biggest groups,
Huey Lewis and the News and the Doobie Brothers, are making ready to tour.
Huey and the boys -- after warm-up shows at the NARM convention in San
Francisco and the Ritz in New York in April -- will hit the road in July. The
Doobies' tour debuts in Fresno on May 30 and comes to Shoreline Amphitheater
on June 1.;    HE OUGHT TO BE ON RADIO -- Speaking of Huey Lewis, he will be
the featured guest on the "Rockline" program 8:30 p.m. Monday on KRQR-FM
(97.3).;    ON WITH THE SHOWS -- It's called "Lollapalooza," and it is just
that -- one of the real knockout tours of the season. It stars Jane's
Addiction, Siouxsie and the Banshees, Living Colour, Nine Inch Nails, Ice-T,
Butthole Surfers and the Henry Rollins Band, and it is scheduled to haul into
Shoreline Amphitheater July 26 at 2 p.m. Tickets are $25 and $20; they go on
sale Sunday. Also Sunday, tickets go on sale for the Scorpions, who also
perform at Shoreline June 22 at 7 p.m. Price: $22.50 and $19.50. For both
shows, call (408) 998-2277 or (415) 762-2277.  </TEXT>
