<TEXT>  Buy high-quality tools that are backed by a warranty. If you choose a power
tool, make certain that parts and local service are readily available.;   
Books; Here are some of my current favorites for the how-to reader:;   
(check) "The Weekend Refinisher," by Bruce Johnson (Ballantine Books, $8.95).
Many books on refinishing are too technical or require artistic skills. This
book is for those of us who want to attain good results without a lot of
special equipment and supplies. A real value for the price.;    (check)
"Year-Round House Care," by Graham Blackburn and the editors of Consumer
Reports Books (Consumer's Union, $14.95). A good, basic overview of home
maintenance and repair. A nice gift for a father in a new home.;    (check)
"Popular Mechanics Home How-To," edited by Albert Jackson and David Day
(Hearst/William Morrow, $30). This is a compilation and revision of the
Collins Complete Do-It-Yourself Manual. It is thorough, easy to understand and
loaded with helpful do-it-yourself information. Until another publisher
revises its do-it-yourself encyclopedia, this is my favorite.;    (check) "The
Complete Manual of Woodworking," by Albert Jackson, David Day and Simon
Jennings (Alfred A. Knopf, $40). At that price it's probably not a book the
average do-it-yourselfer who has an interest in design, techniques and tools
would buy. That's why it's an ideal gift. Not only is the book well-written,
but the illustrations make it easily understandable.;    Have a happy Father's
Day.;  Hang plants from a joist; Q How do we hang plants from the ceiling so
that they won't fall?; A Even though there are hangers sold that simply
instruct you to hang plants from "anywhere on the ceiling," your hanger should
be anchored well into a ceiling joist -- a joist is one of the boards that
make the framework for your ceiling.;    Use a magnetic stud finder to locate
nails that attach the ceiling dry wall to the joist. Once several nails are
located you can get a pretty good idea of the position of the joist. If none
is in the area where you want to hang the plant and you have access to the
attic space, you will need to nail a section of 2-by-4 between joists so that
you have something firm to attach a hanger to.;    If you don't have attic
access, it can be quite a job adding the proper foundation for the hanger. To
keep a chunk of ceiling -- and the plant -- from falling on your head, it
might be best to find another location where there's a joist.  </TEXT>
