<LEADPARA>  PEACEFUL protest comes in many forms.;    When Alex Cordia waves her hand, she
sends a message for patriotism but mostly for peace.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PATRIOTIC PINKIES
RED, WHITE AND BLUE NAILS SUPPORT THE TROOPS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  WAR IN THE GULF  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Cordia, a fingernail artist at Paradise Nails in Reseda, has 400 tiny
rhinestones individually glued in the shape of a flag to the 3-inch nail on
her left-hand ring finger. The process takes four hours. The ring finger on
her right reads: "World Peace," written in red, white and blue rhinestones.;  
 "We don't want anybody to go to war," says Cordia, who says her brother,
Anthony, served in Vietnam and that her boyfriend died during that war.;   
Holiday wear;    Client Sandy Shapiro sometimes has a flag painted on her
acrylic nails for holidays such as the Fourth of July. Shapiro wears
rhinestone flags, victory "V's" and red, white and blue swirls as a way to
support the troops in Saudi Arabia.;    "With all this going on in the gulf,
and with my boyfriend over there -- and everyone over there -- I said to Alex:
'Let's do all red, white and blue. Let's put on peace signs and flags," says
Shapiro, a legal secretary from Woodland Hills.;    Caring for America;    "We
started doing the nails for people who wanted to express their caring for the
United States," Cordia says. "One client just had a friend report to the
gulf.";    The nail art has a purpose beyond the aesthetic, according to
Cordia.;    "People express their feelings through their nails," she says.
"Some people picket. We picket quieter. We don't stand on the corner with
signs. We flash our 3-inch fingernails. We flash, and people look."  </TEXT>
