<LEADPARA>  Q I don't want to damage the brick fascia on the front of my house's entry by
drilling into the bricks, but I need to anchor some light fixtures and an
address sign to the wall. A hardware store clerk has told me that I can't put
screw anchors into the mortar between bricks. Is this true and what is an
alternative?;   A Mortar doesn't always fill in completely the area between
bricks, and will sometimes crumble when drilled. That's the reason the clerk
is cautioning you.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Home  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MORTAR OK FOR ANCHORING FIXTURES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Do It Yourself  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     However, unless the light fixtures and address sign are heavy cast iron, I
think you can still put anchors into the mortar. Use anchors threaded to
receive quarter-inch bolts. Drill a hole in the mortar slightly larger in
diameter and deeper than the size of the anchor. Coat the bolt threads with a
mold-releasing agent or silicone spray and screw the bolt into the anchor.
This will minimize epoxy getting onto the anchor threads.;   Mix enough
two-part epoxy to liberally coat the inside and back of the hole. Insert the
anchor flush with the face of the adjoining bricks (not flush with the face of
the mortar). Allow the epoxy to fully cure according to the manufacturer's
instructions before removing the bolt. You may find that it's necessary to
enlarge the mounting holes in your light fixtures to accommodate the
quarter-inch bolt.; Q I bought an older home with a semifinished basement. An
all-purpose room has been finished with paneling over block walls and a
dry-wall ceiling. The room always has a musty odor and I suspect that moisture
is coming through the blocks and getting trapped behind the paneling. This is
the only area of the basement that has this odor. How can I check the wall
behind the paneling?;   A I assume that you've carefully checked all other
wall areas in the basement for any signs of leaks and that your all-purpose
room is not trapping moisture from an adjoining clothes dryer, shower or other
source. If the paneling has been nailed to furring strips, use a nail set and
drive the finishing nails through the panels (remove the top nails last). If
the panels have been glued in place they probably will need to be pried off
the wall and won't be reusable.;   Inspect the exposed blocks for water
stains, mold, mildew -- any sign of moisture. Your most effective time to
search for dampness or a leak is immediately after a heavy rain.;   Before
replacing the paneling, securely tape a one-foot-square piece of aluminum foil
to the block wall, about 16 inches below the exterior soil line. Make sure
that you tape all around the edges to seal them well.;   Periodically check
the aluminum foil for moisture on the side facing into the room. After three
days, remove the tape and see if there is any moisture accumulation on the
side of the foil that has been facing the wall. Moisture accumulation on the
room side of the foil indicates condensation and that the source of moisture
is from within the room. Moisture on the wall side means that moisture is
coming through the wall, and the wall will require repair or sealing. (There
are health hazards associated with using some masonry sealers indoors. Read
warnings carefully.);   Nailed panels can be renailed to the furring strips
and the holes patched with a matching putty stick. It's possible that moisture
could be seeping up the paneling from a concrete floor, so inspect the floor
as well.  </TEXT>
